          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>The deep cerebellar nuclei are arranged medial to lateral as fastigial, globosus</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>The deep cerebellar nuclei are arranged medial to lateral as fastigial, globosus, emboliformis, and dentate. Which of these is the largest and serves as the primary output nucleus for coordinated voluntary movement?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Fastigial nucleus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The fastigial is the most medial nucleus. It receives input from the vermis and projects to the vestibular nuclei, primarily controlling balance and axial posture — not limb coordination.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Dentate nucleus</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The dentate is the largest deep cerebellar nucleus. Its fibres exit via the superior cerebellar peduncle, relay through the ventrolateral thalamus, and reach the motor cortex to plan and execute skilled voluntary movements.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Globosus nucleus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The globosus, together with the emboliformis, forms the interposed nuclei. These receive input from the paravermal zone and help modulate limb movements, but the dentate is the largest and principal output nucleus.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Emboliformis nucleus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The emboliformis is part of the interposed nuclei group. While it contributes to motor output, it is much smaller than the dentate, which is the dominant output nucleus for skilled voluntary movement.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The dentate nucleus is the largest and most lateral of the four deep cerebellar nuclei. Use the mnemonic FGED — Feel Good Every Day — to recall their medial-to-lateral arrangement."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done! Remember the mnemonic 'Feel Good Every Day' for the medial-to-lateral sequence: Fastigial → Globosus → Emboliformis → Dentate."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
