        {
          "duration": {
            "from": 330.375,
            "to": 340.375
          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Cerebellar signs are characteristically ipsilateral — a right cerebellar hemisph</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Cerebellar signs are characteristically ipsilateral — a right cerebellar hemisphere lesion causes right-sided limb ataxia. What is the anatomical basis for this ipsilateral pattern?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Cerebellar output crosses twice: at the superior cerebellar peduncle and at the pyramidal decussation</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Dentate fibres cross first in the midbrain (superior cerebellar peduncle) to reach the contralateral thalamus and motor cortex. The corticospinal tract then crosses again at the medullary pyramids. Two crossings bring the signal back to the original side.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Cerebellar efferents travel in uncrossed ipsilateral tracts throughout their course</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Cerebellar output does cross — fibres decussate at the superior cerebellar peduncle in the midbrain. The ipsilateral pattern results from a second crossing at the pyramidal decussation, not from an absence of crossing.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The inferior cerebellar peduncle carries only uncrossed proprioceptive afferents</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>While the dorsal spinocerebellar tract entering through the inferior peduncle is largely ipsilateral input, this describes afferent pathways, not efferent output. The double crossing of the efferent pathway is the key mechanism.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Purkinje cells project directly to ipsilateral lower motor neurones in the spinal cord</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Purkinje cells project to the deep cerebellar nuclei, not directly to spinal motor neurones. The efferent pathway passes through the thalamus and motor cortex before reaching the cord via the corticospinal tract.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Cerebellar signs are ipsilateral because the output pathway crosses twice: once at the superior cerebellar peduncle (midbrain) and once at the pyramidal decussation. Two crossings = same side."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Excellent! The double-crossing rule is clinically important — it explains why a right PICA infarct produces right-sided cerebellar ataxia, not left."
                }
              ],
